emphasis.docTitle:
A review of the African snake-eyed skinks ( Scincidae :
Panaspis
) from Angola , with the description of a new species

subSection.paragraph:
The end of the armed conflicts that ravaged the southwestern African country of Angola for almost four decades presents a new and unparalleled opportunity for local and international researchers to study the rich yet poorly documented biodiversity of the country. Within the sub-Saharan African region, Angola is one of the most diverse countries in terms of biomes and habitats, contributing directly to its overall numbers of biological diversity, high rates of endemism and complex biogeographic patterns (Marques et al. 2019;
Huntley et al. 2019
). Sitting at the geographic transition between Central/West Africa and Southern Africa, the country hosts a spectacular diversity of taxonomic lineages representative of both these areas (
Marques et al. 2018
). The new studies on Angolan biodiversity have analyzed a wide diversity of taxonomic groups (
Huntley et al. 2019
) with herpetofauna being one of the groups that has attracted significant attention (
Marques et al. 2018
). These recent studies include the description of new species (
Conradie et al. 2012a
,b, 2013;
Stanley et al. 2016
; Ceríaco et al. 2018b ;
Marques et al. 2019a
,b;
Branch et al. 2019a
,b), surveys of poorly explored areas (
Ceríaco et al. 2014
, 2016a ,b, 2018c; Branch & Conradie 2015 ;
Conradie et al. 2016
;
Baptista et al. 2018
;
Butler et al. 2019
) and the rediscovery of rare and elusive species (Heinicke et al. 2017;
Gonçalves et al. 2019
).

Panaspis breviceps ( Peters, 1873 )
, was originally described from Gabon , and its current known geographic distribution encompasses the Central African Republic , Nigeria , Cameroon , Equatorial Guinea (Bioko Island), Ghana , Gabon , the northern Democratic Republic of the Congo , and a disjunct isolated population in the escarpment areas of northwestern Angola ( Schmitz et al. 2005 ;
Marques et al. 2018
). The species is the largest of the genus in Angola , typically exceeding twice the snout-vent length of all other species occurring in the country. Parker (1936) noted five specimens of this Central/West African species from Congulu, Kwanza Sul Province , collected during the Karl Jordan expedition to Angola and Namibia . The only other available records of this species in the country are based on specimens in the collections of the Field Museum of Natural History ( FMNH ), Chicago, and the Museum of Comparative Zoology ( MCZ ), Harvard University, both collected by Gert Heinrich in Roça Canzele, 30 km West of Camabatela, Kwanza Norte Province, in 1954. The species was conservatively maintained as a member of the genus Panapsis by
Medina et al. (2016)
, who, however, noted that it belongs to a relatively divergent clade and that its taxonomic status may change with improved sampling. The taxonomic identity of the specimens recorded by Parker (1936) and those in the collections of the FMNH and MCZ have never been critically reviewed. Taking into account that these are the only records of the species for the country and that this putative Angolan population represents a disjunct population, isolated from the closest available records by almost 1000 km , its taxonomic identity requires attention.

Uncorrected pairwise sequence divergences of cytb sequences were calculated in MEGA X. For phylogenetic analysis, a concatenated data set was constructed containing sequences of all four genes. PartitionFinder 2.1.1 (
Lanfear et al ., 2016
) was used to choose a partitioning scheme and identify best-fitting models of evolution for the concatenated data set. A greedy search was implemented in which each gene and each codon position of the protein-coding genes was considered a potential separate partition. Based on this search, the data set was divided into eight subsets using the following models of evolution: 16s (GTR+I+γ), cyt b position 1 (TVMef+I+γ), cytb position 2 (TrN+I+γ), cytb position 3 (TIM+I+γ), pdc position 1 (F81), pdc position 2 (F81+І), pdc position 3 and rag1 position 3 (GTR+γ), rag1 position 1 and 2 (HKY+γ). A maximum likelihood phylogenetic analysis was then performed using this partition scheme in IQ-TREE 1.5.5 (
Nguyen et al ., 2014
), with branch support assessed using 1000 rapid bootstraps.

Distribution. The species is distributed through West and Central Africa, from Cameroon to the Central African Republic , Bioko Island, Gabon , the Democratic Republic of the Congo and northwestern Angola (
Schmitz et al. 2005
). In Angola the species is currently only known from the north-western escarpment zone in Kwanza Norte and Kwanza Sul provinces ( Fig. 6 ).

